Actually, &quot;Yes&quot; and &quot;No.&quot;  Cuban Air Force Major Orestes Lorenzo Pérez did indeed defect to the United States by flying his MiG-23 to Naval Air Station - Key West on March 20, 1991.  As per international law and custom, the aircraft would be returned to Cuba (the take-off depicted here).  However, in what would make a great movie some day, as per Wikipedia (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Cold_War_pilot_defections" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Cold_War_pilot_defections</a>):
&quot;On December 19, 1992 he returned to Cuba in a small, twin-engined 1961 Cessna 310, landing on the coastal highway of El Mamey beach in Varadero, Matanzas Province, 93 miles from Havana at the agreed time. His wife Victoria (34), and their two sons, Reyneil (11), and Alejandro (6), were already waiting on his order delivered through two Mexican ladies as a messengers few days before. Orestes Lorenzo Pérez picked up his family and managed a successful safe return to Marathon, Florida.&quot;
